# Day 6 - Linux User Data Transfer

## Task
Locate all regular files owned by `kareem` within `/home/usersdata` on App Server 2 and copy them to `/official` while preserving the directory structure.

## Objective
Practice finding files by ownership and copying them safely without flattening the source folder structure.

## Commands Used
```bash
ssh steve@stapp02

find /home/usersdata -type f -user kareem -exec cp --parents {} /official \;
```

## What the Commands Do
- `ssh steve@stapp02` connects to App Server 2.
- `find /home/usersdata` searches the source directory tree.
- `-type f` limits results to regular files only.
- `-user kareem` filters files owned by `kareem`.
- `-exec cp --parents {} /official \;` copies each file and preserves its parent path structure inside `/official`.

## Verification
Checked that the expected files were copied into `/official` with their directory paths preserved.

## What I Learned
- How to filter files by ownership using `find`.
- How to avoid copying directories when only files are required.
- How `cp --parents` preserves directory structure during copy operations.
- Why structure-preserving copies matter in backups and data recovery.

## Personal Notes
This task showed how useful `find` is for operational work. It also reinforced that copying data safely is not just about moving files, but about preserving context and paths.
